# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geochronology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The **12-hour clock** is a time convention in which the 24 hours of the day are divided into two periods: **a.m.** (from Latin ***ante meridiem***, translating to "before midday") and **p.m.** (from Latin ***post meridiem***, translating to "after midday").
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock has been developed since the second millennium BC and reached its modern form in the 16th century.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour time convention is common in several English-speaking nations and former British colonies, as well as a few other countries.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In English-speaking countries: "12 p.m." usually indicates noon, while "12 a.m." means midnight, but the reverse convention has also been used (see § Confusion at noon and midnight).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The natural day-and-night division of a calendar day forms the fundamental basis as to why each day is split into two cycles.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Originally there were two cycles: one cycle which could be tracked by the position of the Sun (day), followed by one cycle which could be tracked by the Moon and stars (night).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This eventually evolved into the two 12-hour periods which are used today, one called "a.m." starting at midnight and another called "p.m." starting at noon.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock can be traced back as far as Mesopotamia and ancient Egypt.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Both an Egyptian sundial for daytime use and an Egyptian water clock for night-time use were found in the tomb of Pharaoh Amenhotep I.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] 1500 BC, these clocks divided their respective times of use into 12 hours each.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The ancient Romans also used a 12-hour clock: daylight and nighttime were each divided into 12 equal intervals (of varying duration according to the season).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The nighttime hours were grouped into four *watches* (*vigiliae*).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The first mechanical clocks in the 14th century, if they had dials at all, showed all 24 hours using the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by astronomers' familiarity with the astrolabe and sundial and by their desire to model the Earth's apparent motion around the Sun.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In Northern Europe these dials generally used the 12-hour numbering scheme in Roman numerals but showed both *a.m.* and *p.m.* periods in sequence.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This is known as the double-XII system and can be seen on many surviving clock faces, such as those at Wells and Exeter.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Elsewhere in Europe, numbering was more likely to be based on the 24-hour system (I to XXIV).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock was used throughout the British Empire.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] During the 15th and 16th centuries, the 12-hour analog dial and time system gradually became established as standard throughout Northern Europe for general public use.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The 24-hour analog dial was reserved for more specialized applications, such as astronomical clocks and chronometers.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Most analog clocks and watches today use the 12-hour dial, on which the shorter hour hand rotates once every 12 hours and twice in one day.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Some analog clock dials have an inner ring of numbers along with the standard 1-to-12 numbered ring.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The number 12 is paired either with a 00 or a 24, while the numbers 1 through 11 are paired with the numbers 13 through 23, respectively.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This modification allows the clock to also be read in 24-hour notation.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This kind of 12-hour clock can be found in countries where the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Even in those countries where the 12-hour clock is predominant, there are frequently contexts (such as science, medicine, the military or transport) in which the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In most countries, however, the 24-hour clock is the standard system used, especially in writing.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Some nations in Europe and Latin America use a combination of the two, preferring the 12-hour system in colloquial speech but using the 24-hour system in written form and in formal contexts.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock in speech often uses phrases such as*... in the morning*,*... in the afternoon*,*... in the evening*, and *... at night*.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] *Rider's British Merlin* almanac for 1795 and a similar almanac for 1773 published in London used them.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Other than in English-speaking countries and some Spanish-speaking countries, the terms *a.m.* and *p.m.* are seldom used and often unknown.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In most countries, computers by default show the time in 24-hour notation.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Most operating systems, including Microsoft Windows and Unix-like systems such as Linux and macOS, activate the 12-hour notation by default for a limited number of language and region settings.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This behaviour can be changed by the user, such as with the Windows operating system's "Region and Language" settings.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The Latin abbreviations *a.m.* and *p.m.* (often written "am" and "pm", "AM" and "PM", or "A.M." and "P.M.") are used in English (and Spanish).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] When abbreviations and phrases are omitted, one may rely on sentence context and societal norms to reduce ambiguity.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] For example, if one commutes to work at "9:00", 9:00 a.m. may be implied, but if a social dance is scheduled to begin at "9:00", it may begin at 9:00 p.m.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The terms "a.m." and "p.m." are abbreviations of the Latin *ante meridiem* (before midday) and *post meridiem* (after midday).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Depending on the style guide referenced, the abbreviations "a.m." and "p.m." are variously written in small capitals ("am" and "pm"), uppercase letters without a period ("AM" and "PM"), uppercase letters with periods, or lowercase letters ("am" and "pm" or "a.m." and "p.m.").
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Some style guides suggest the use of a space between the number and the a.m. or p.m. abbreviation.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Style guides recommend not using a.m. and p.m. without a time preceding it.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The hour/minute separator varies between countries: some use a colon, others use a period (full stop), and still others use the letter h.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] (In some usages, particularly "military time", of the 24-hour clock, there is no separator between hours and minutes.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In speaking, it is common to round the time to the nearest five minutes and/or express the time as the past (or to) the closest hour; for example, "five past five" (5:05).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Minutes *past* the hour means those minutes are added to the hour; "ten past five" means 5:10.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Minutes *to, till* and *of* the hour mean those minutes are subtracted; "ten of five", "ten till five", and "ten to five" all mean 4:50.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Fifteen minutes is often called a *quarter hour*, and thirty minutes is often known as a *half hour*.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] For example, 5:15 can be phrased "(a) quarter past five" or "five-fifteen"; 5:30 can be "half past five", "five-thirty" or simply "half five".
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] The time 8:45 may be spoken as "eight forty-five" or "(a) quarter to nine".
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Polish, rounding off is mandatory when using (spoken) 12-hour clock, but disallowed when using 24 hour notation.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] 15:12 might be pronounced as "quarter past three" or "fifteen-twelve", but *not* "three-twelve" or "quarter past fifteen".
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In older English, it was common for the number 25 to be expressed as "five-and-twenty".
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In this way the time 8:35 might have been phrased as "five-and-twenty to 9", although this styling fell out of fashion in the later part of the 1900s and is now rarely used.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Instead of meaning 5:30, the "half five" expression is sometimes used to mean 4:30, or "halfway to five", especially for regions such as the American Midwest and other areas that have been particularly influenced by German culture.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This meaning follows the pattern choices of many Germanic and Slavic languages, including Serbo-Croatian, Dutch, Danish, Russian, Norwegian, and Swedish, as well as Hungarian, Finnish, and the languages of the Baltic States.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Moreover, in situations where the relevant hour is obvious or has been recently mentioned, a speaker might omit the hour and just say "quarter to (the hour)", "half past" or "ten till" to avoid an elaborate sentence in informal conversations.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] These forms are often commonly used in television and radio broadcasts that cover multiple time zones at one-hour intervals.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Minutes may be expressed as an exact number of minutes past the hour specifying the time of day (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is "six thirty-two").
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Additionally, when expressing the time using the "past (after)" or "to (before)" formula, it is conventional to choose the number of minutes below 30 (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is conventionally "twenty-eight minutes to seven" rather than "thirty-two minutes past six").
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In spoken English, full hours are often represented by the numbered hour followed by *o'clock* (10:00 as *ten o'clock*, 2:00 as *two o'clock*).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] This may be followed by the "a.m." or "p.m." designator, though some phrases such as *in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening,* or *at night* more commonly follow analog-style terms such as *o'clock, half past three,* and *quarter to four.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] O'clock* itself may be omitted, telling a time as *four a.m.* or *four p.m.* Minutes ":01" to ":09" are usually pronounced as *oh one* to *oh nine* (*nought* or *zero* can also be used instead of *oh*).
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Minutes ":10" to ":59" are pronounced as their usual number-words.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] For instance, 6:02 a.m. can be pronounced *six oh two a.m.* whereas 6:32 a.m. could be told as *six thirty-two a.m.*.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] It is not always clear what times "12:00 a.m." and "12:00 p.m." denote.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] In Latin, **ante meridiem** (a.m.) means "before midday" and **post meridiem** (p.m.) means "after midday".
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Since noon is neither before nor after itself, the terms a.m. and p.m. do not apply.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Although noon could be denoted "12 m.", this is seldom done and also does not resolve the question of how to indicate midnight.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] By convention, "12 a.m." denotes midnight and "12 p.m." denotes noon.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] However, many style guides recommend against using either because of the potential for confusion.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Many recommend instead using the unambiguous terms "12 noon" and "12 midnight", or simply "noon" and "midnight".
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] These include *The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language*, *The Canadian Press Stylebook*, and the NIST's "Frequently asked questions (FAQ)" web page.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Alternatively, some recommend referring to one minute before or after 12:00, especially when referring to midnight (for example, "11:59 p.m." or "12:01 a.m.").
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] These include the UK's National Physical Laboratory "FAQ-Time" web page.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] That has become common in the United States in legal contracts and for airplane, bus, or train schedules, though some schedules use other conventions.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Occasionally, when trains run at regular intervals, the pattern may be broken at midnight by displacing the midnight departure one or more minutes, such as to 11:59 p.m. or 12:01 a.m.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Some authors have been known to use the reverse of the normal convention.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Richards in his book *Mapping Time* (1999) provided a diagram in which 12 a.m. means noon and 12 p.m. means midnight.
[src:geochronology/12-hour-clock] Historically, the style manual of the United States Government Printing Office used 12 a.m. for noon and 12 p.m. for midnight, though this was reversed in its 2008 editions.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Clocks and watches with a **24-hour analog dial** have an hour hand that makes one complete revolution—360°—in a full day, or 24 hours per revolution.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In contrast, the more familiar 12-hour analog dial has an hour hand that completes two revolutions per day, or 12 hours per revolution.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Twenty-four-hour analog clocks and watches are commonly used by logistics workers, firefighters, police officers, paramedics, nurses, pilots, scientists, and military personnel.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] They are often preferred because they present an unambiguous representation of the entire day at once.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] This definition specifically refers to the use of a full circular dial to represent a 24-hour cycle.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Simply using numbers from 0 to 23 (or 1 to 24) is known as the *24-hour clock system*.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials also use 24-hour analog dials, as the shadow follows a path that repeats approximately once per day.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many sundials are marked with the double-XII (or double-12) system, where the numbers I to XII (or 1 to 12) appear twice—once for the morning and once for the afternoon and evening.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Thus, VI (6) appears twice on many sundial dials: once near sunrise and once near sunset.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Modern 24-hour analog dials—aside from sundials—are almost always marked with 24 numbers or hour markers around the edge, following the 24-hour clock system.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Because they display the entire day in one rotation, they do not require AM or PM indicators.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The ancient Egyptians divided the day into 24 hours.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] There are diagrams of circles divided into 24 sections in the astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senemut.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials use some or all of the 24-hour dial, because they show the position of the sun in the sky.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sometimes, for aesthetic rather than practical reasons, all the 24 hour marks are shown.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Medieval clocks often used the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by the widespread example of the astrolabe.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Northern Europe, the double-XII system was preferred: two sets of the Roman numerals I to XII were used, one on the left side for the night and morning hours, and another set on the right side of the dial to represent the afternoon and evening hours.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Italy, the numbers from 1 to 24 (I to XXIV in Roman numerals) were used, leading to the widespread use of the 24-hour system in that country.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] On Italian clocks, though, the I was often shown at the right side of the dial, rather than the top.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] This probably reflects the influence of the Italian timekeeping system, which started counting the hours of the day at sunset or twilight.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In northern Europe, the double-XII system was gradually superseded during the 14th and 15th centuries by the single-XII (12-hour system), leading to the widespread adoption of the 12-hour dial for popular use.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 24-hour analog dial continued to be used, but primarily by technicians, astronomers, scientists, and clockmakers.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] John Harrison, Thomas Tompion, and Mudge built a number of clocks with 24-hour analog dials, particularly when building astronomical and nautical instruments.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour dials were also used on sidereal clocks.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The famous Big Ben clock in London has a 24-hour dial as part of the mechanism, although it is not visible from the outside.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Astronauts used the 24-hour format due to the lack of day/night in the space environment.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 20th century, the 24-hour analog dial was adopted by radio amateurs, media, pilots, maritime, submariners, government, diplomats and for military use.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour analog watches and clocks are still being manufactured today, and are sought after by collectors and enthusiasts.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Manufacturers who make 24-hour analog watches include Glycine, Raketa, Vostok, Fortis, Poljot, Swatch, and many others.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] A few rare variants place noon and midnight at the right and left sides.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] There is no ambiguity if the 24-hour numbering is used.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the United States, the government and military commonly use 24-hour clocks having noon at the bottom; the variant with noon at the top is far less common.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Multiple time zones can be displayed by having multiple hour hands or a rotating bezel.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel is a ring around the outside of the watch's face.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] When it is used, the top of the watch always represents midnight (or noon) GMT.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel, which also has hour markings, is then rotated so that its numbering represents local time.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] So, a pilot always has GMT time available for talking to air traffic control and, when they land, only has to rotate the bezel to "set" the watch to their new local time.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Glycine was the first to feature a 24-hour rotating bezel in 1953 with the Airman No.1 pilot watch.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The design became widely known when Rolex designed the Rolex GMT Master for Pan-Am pilots in 1954.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] A 24-hour watch with a compass card dial can be used to determine direction when set to local noon and used in conjunction with the Sun.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many (but not all) digital watches can be set to show the time in 24-hour format.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] A common use for the 24-hour analog method of representing time is for showing the way the time of day depends on one's location.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] George Orwell uses the 12-hour and 24-hour dials to symbolize the old and new worlds in his novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 12-hour dial is a relic of pre-revolutionary society, used to represent the desirable past; the 24-hour dial and time system is the compulsory standard imposed by the Party, and represents both conformity and the undesirable nature of the new world.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] It was a bright cold day in April, and the clocks were striking thirteen.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 1927 film *Metropolis*, the opening scene shows both a 24-hour analog clock and a 10-hour (decimal) analog clock, one above the other.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] Both are used to convey the impression of an alien and highly efficient society.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Jules Verne's 1870 science fiction masterpiece *Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas*, Captain Nemo remarks that the clocks in the *Nautilus* use a 24-hour dial: "Now, look at that clock: it's electric, it runs with an accuracy rivaling the finest chronometers.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] I've had it divided into twenty–four hours like Italian clocks, since neither day nor night, sun nor moon, exist for me, but only this artificial light that I import into the depths of the seas!
[src:geochronology/24-hour-analogue-dial] A watch with a 24-hour analog dial is important to the resolution of Alfred Bester's 1953 short story "The Roller Coaster".
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The modern **24-hour clock** is the convention of timekeeping in which the day runs from midnight to midnight and is divided into 24 hours.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] This is indicated by the hours (and minutes) passed since midnight, from 00(:00) to 23(:59), with 24(:00) as an option to indicate the end of the day.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] This system, as opposed to the 12-hour clock, is the most commonly used time notation in the world today, and is used by the international standard ISO 8601.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] A number of countries, particularly English speaking, use the 12-hour clock, or a mixture of the 24- and 12-hour time systems.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In countries where the 12-hour clock is dominant, some professions prefer to use the 24-hour clock.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] For example, in the practice of medicine, the 24-hour clock is generally used in documentation of care as it prevents any ambiguity as to when events occurred in a patient's medical history.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] To indicate the exact end of the day, hh may take the value 24, with mm and ss taking the value 00.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In the case of a leap second, the value of ss may extend to 60.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] A leading zero is added for numbers under 10, but it is optional for the hours.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The leading zero is very commonly used in computer applications, and always used when a specification requires it (for example, ISO 8601).
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Where subsecond resolution is required, the seconds can be a decimal fraction; that is, the fractional part follows a decimal dot or comma, as in 01:23:45.678.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The most commonly used separator symbol between hours, minutes and seconds is the colon, which is also the symbol used in ISO 8601.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In the past, some European countries used the dot on the line as a separator, but most national standards on time notation have since then been changed to the international standard colon.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In some contexts (including some computer protocols and military time), no separator is used and times are written as, for example, "2359".
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In the 24-hour time notation, the day begins at midnight, 00:00 or 0:00, and the last minute of the day begins at 23:59.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In the ISO 8601 notation, 24:00 may also be used to refer to midnight at the end of a given date — that is, 24:00 of one day is the same time as 00:00 of the following day.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The notation 24:00 mainly serves to refer to the exact end of a day in a time interval.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] A typical usage is giving opening hours ending at midnight (e.g.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Similarly, some bus and train timetables show 00:00 as departure time and 24:00 as arrival time.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Legal contracts often run from the start date at 00:00 until the end date at 24:00.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] While the 24-hour notation unambiguously distinguishes between midnight at the start (00:00) and end (24:00) of any given date, there is no commonly accepted distinction among users of the 12-hour notation.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Style guides and military communication regulations in some English-speaking countries discourage the use of 24:00 even in the 24-hour notation, and recommend reporting times near midnight as 23:59 or 00:01 instead.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Sometimes the use of 00:00 is also avoided.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In variance with this, an older version of the correspondence manual for the United States Navy and United States Marine Corps specified 0001 to 2400.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The manual was updated in June 2015 to use 0000 to 2359.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Time-of-day notations beyond 24:00 (such as 24:01 or 25:00 instead of 00:01 or 01:00) are not commonly used and not covered by the relevant standards.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] However, they have been used occasionally in some special contexts in the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Canada, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, and China where business hours extend beyond midnight, such as broadcast television production and scheduling.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The GTFS public transport schedule listings file format has the concept of service days and expects times beyond 24:00 for trips that run after midnight.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] For example, Microsoft Windows and macOS activate the 12-hour notation by default only if a computer is in a handful of specific language and region settings.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The 24-hour system is commonly used in text-based interfaces.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] POSIX programs such as `ls` default to displaying timestamps in 24-hour format.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In the United States (a country which uses 12-hour clocks), the 24-hour clock is often referred to as *military time*.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] There is, however, a more specific standard for military time which refines the acceptable written and spoken forms of times on the 24-hour clock.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The first mechanical public clocks introduced in Italy were mechanical 24-hour clocks which counted the 24 hours of the day from one-half hour after sunset to the evening of the following day.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The 24th hour was the last hour of day time.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The modern 24-hour system is a late-19th century adaptation of the German midnight-starting system, and then prevailed in the world with the exception of some Anglophone countries.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Striking clocks had to produce 300 strokes each day, which required a lot of rope, and wore out the mechanism quickly, so some localities switched to ringing sequences of 1 to 12 twice, or 1 to 6 repeated four times.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Sandford Fleming, the engineer-in-chief of the Canadian Intercolonial Railway, was an early proponent of using the 24-hour clock as part of a programme to reform timekeeping, which also included establishing time zones and a standard prime meridian.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The Canadian Pacific Railway was among the first organisations to adopt the 24-hour clock, at midsummer 1886.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] A report by a government committee in the United Kingdom noted Italy as the first country among those mentioned to adopt 24-hour time nationally, in 1893.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Other European countries followed: France adopted it in 1912 (the French army in 1909), followed by Denmark (1916), and Greece (1917).
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] By 1920, Spain, Portugal, Belgium, and Switzerland had switched, followed by Turkey (1925), and Germany (1927).
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] By the early 1920s, many countries in Latin America had also adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] Some of the railways in India had switched before the outbreak of the war.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] During World War I, the British Royal Navy adopted the 24-hour clock in 1915, and the Allied armed forces followed soon after, with the British Army switching officially in 1918.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The Canadian armed forces first started to use the 24-hour clock in late 1917.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In 1920, the United States Navy was the first United States organisation to adopt the system; the United States Army, however, did not officially adopt the 24-hour clock until 1 July 1942.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The use of the 24-hour clock in the United Kingdom has grown steadily since the beginning of the 20th century, although attempts to make the system official failed more than once.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In 1934, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) switched to the 24-hour clock for broadcast announcements and programme listings.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] The experiment was halted after five months following a lack of enthusiasm from the public, and the BBC continued using the 12-hour clock.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In the same year, Pan American World Airways Corporation and Western Airlines in the United States both adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] In modern times, the BBC uses a mixture of both the 12-hour and the 24-hour clock.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] British Rail, London Transport, and the London Underground switched to the 24-hour clock for timetables in 1964.
[src:geochronology/24-hour-clock] A mixture of the 12- and 24-hour clocks similarly prevails in other English-speaking Commonwealth countries: French speakers have adopted the 24-hour clock in Canada much more broadly than English speakers, and Australia as well as New Zealand also use both systems.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] In metaphysics, the **A series** and the **B series** are two different descriptions of the temporal ordering relation among events.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] The two series differ principally in their use of tense to describe the temporal relation between events and the resulting ontological implications regarding time.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] John McTaggart introduced these terms in 1908, in an argument for the unreality of time.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] They are now commonly used by contemporary philosophers of time.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Metaphysical debate about temporal orderings reaches back to the ancient Greek philosophers Heraclitus and Parmenides.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Parmenides thought that reality is timeless and unchanging.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Heraclitus, in contrast, believed that the world is a process of ceaseless change, flux and decay.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Reality for Heraclitus is dynamic and ephemeral, in a state of constant flux, as in his famous statement that it is impossible to step twice into the same river (since the river is flowing).
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] McTaggart distinguished the ancient conceptions as a set of relations.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] According to McTaggart, there are two distinct modes in which all events can be ordered in time.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] In the first mode (the A series of temporal positions), events are ordered as future, present, and past.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Futurity and pastness allow for degrees, while the present does not.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] When we speak of time in this way, we are speaking in terms of a series of positions which run from the remote past through the recent past to the present, and from the present through the near future all the way to the remote future.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] The essential characteristic of this descriptive modality is **McTaggartian change**: the continual transformation of an event's position within the series of temporal positions, whereby the event is first future, then present, and then past.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] In this sense, change is understood as temporal passage itself, through which events acquire and lose the determinations of futurity, presentness, and pastness.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Moreover, assertions made according to this modality correspond to the temporal perspective of the person who utters them.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] This is the A series of temporal positions.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Although originally McTaggart defined tenses as relational qualities, i.e., qualities that events possess by standing in a certain relation to something outside of time (that does not change its position in time), today it is popularly believed that he treated tenses as monadic properties.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Later philosophers have independently inferred that McTaggart must have understood tense as monadic because English tenses are normally expressed by the non-relational singular predicates "is past", "is present" and "is future", as noted by R.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] An important difference between the two series is that while events continuously change their position in the A series, their position in the B series does not.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] If an event is ever earlier than some events and later than the rest, it is always earlier than and later than those very events.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Furthermore, while events acquire their A-series determinations through a relation to something outside of time, their B-series determinations hold between the events that constitute the B series.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] This is the B series, and the philosophy that says all truths about time can be reduced to B series statements is the B-theory of time.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] The logic and the linguistic expression of the two series are radically different.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] The A series is *tensed* and the B series is *tenseless*.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] For example, the assertion "it is raining here today" is a tensed assertion because it depends on the temporal perspective—the present—of the person who utters it, while the assertion "It rained here on 29 June 2026" is tenseless because it does not so depend.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] From the point of view of their truth-values, the two propositions are identical (both true or both false) if the first assertion is made on 29 June 2026.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] The non-temporal relation of precedence between two events, say "E precedes F", does not change over time (excluding from this discussion the issue of the relativity of temporal order of causally disconnected events in the theory of relativity).
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] On the other hand, the character of being "past, present or future" of the events "E" or "F" does change with time.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] In the image of McTaggart the passage of time consists in the fact that terms ever further in the future pass into the present...or that the present advances toward terms ever farther in the future.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the first point of view, we speak as if the B series slides along a fixed A series.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the second point of view, we speak as if the A series slides along a fixed B series.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] There are two principal varieties of the A-theory, presentism and the growing block universe.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Both assume an objective present, but presentism assumes that only present objects exist, while the growing block universe assumes both present and past objects exist, but not future ones.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Views that assume no objective present and are therefore versions of the B-theory include eternalism and four-dimensionalism.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] Vincent Conitzer argues that A-theory is related to Benj Hellie's vertiginous question and Caspar Hare's ideas of egocentric presentism and perspectival realism.
[src:geochronology/a-series-and-b-series] He argues that A-theory being true and "now" being metaphysically distinguished from other moments of time implies that the "I" is also metaphysically distinguished from other first-person perspectives.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Usage of the term was more common during the Renaissance, when editors sometimes added AUC to Roman manuscripts they published, giving the false impression that the convention was commonly used in antiquity.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] In reality, the dominant method of identifying years in Roman times was to name the two consuls who held office that year.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] In late antiquity, regnal years were also in use, as in Roman Egypt during the Diocletian era after AD 293, and in the Byzantine Empire from AD 537, following a decree by Justinian.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Prior to the Roman state's adoption of the Varronian chronology – created by Titus Pomponius Atticus and Marcus Terentius Varro – there were many different dates posited for when the city was founded.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] This state of confusion required picking a canonical founding date for one to use an AUC date.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] The Varronian chronology, constructed from fragmentary sources and demonstrably about four years off of absolute events c.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] 340 BC, placed the founding of the city on 21 April 753 BC.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] This date, likely arrived at by mechanical calculation but accepted with a variance of one year by the Augustan-era *fasti Capitolini*, has become the traditional date.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] AD 41–54) onward, this calculation superseded other contemporary calculations.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Celebrating the anniversary of the city became part of imperial propaganda.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Claudius was the first to hold magnificent celebrations in honor of the anniversary of the city, in AD 47, the eight hundredth year from the founding of the city.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Hadrian, in AD 121, and Antoninus Pius, in AD 147 and AD 148, held similar celebrations respectively.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] In AD 248, Philip the Arab celebrated Rome's first millennium, together with Ludi saeculares for Rome's alleged tenth saeculum.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Coins from his reign commemorate the celebrations.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] A coin by a contender for the imperial throne, Pacatianus, explicitly states "[y]ear one thousand and first", which is an indication that the citizens of the empire had a sense of the beginning of a new era, a *Sæculum Novum*.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] The Anno Domini (AD) year numbering was developed by a monk named Dionysius Exiguus in Rome in AD 525 (AUC 1278), as a result of his work on calculating the date of Easter.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Dionysius did not use the AUC convention, but instead based his calculations on the Diocletian era.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] This convention had been in use since AD 293, the year of the tetrarchy, as it became impractical to use regnal years of the current emperor.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] In his Easter table, the year AD 532 (AUC 1285) was equated with the 248th regnal year of Diocletian.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] Blackburn and Holford-Strevens review interpretations of Dionysius which place the Incarnation in 2 BC, 1 BC, or AD 1.
[src:geochronology/ab-urbe-condita] The year AD 1 corresponds to AUC 754, based on the epoch of Varro.
[src:geochronology/absolute-dating] In archaeology, absolute dating is usually based on the physical, chemical, and life properties of the materials of artifacts, buildings, or other items that have been modified by humans and by historical associations with materials with known dates (such as coins and historical records).
[src:geochronology/absolute-dating] For example, coins found in excavations may have their production date written on them, or there may be written records describing the coin and when it was used, allowing the site to be associated with a particular calendar year.
[src:geochronology/absolute-dating] Absolute dating techniques include radiocarbon dating of wood or bones, potassium-argon dating, and trapped-charge dating methods such as thermoluminescence dating of glazed ceramics.
[src:geochronology/absolute-dating] In some areas of the world, it is possible to date wood back a few thousand years, or even many thousands.
[src:geochronology/absolute-dating] Currently, the maximum for fully anchored chronologies is a little over 11,000 years from present.
[src:geochronology/aspro-chronology] The **ASPRO chronology** is a nine-period dating system of the ancient Near East used by the Maison de l'Orient et de la Méditerranée for archaeological sites aged between 14,000 and 5,700 BP.
[src:geochronology/aspro-chronology] First published in 1994, ASPRO stands for the "Atlas des sites du Proche-Orient" (Atlas of Near East archaeological sites), a French publication pioneered by Francis Hours and developed by other scholars such as Olivier Aurenche.
[src:geochronology/aspro-chronology] In 2001, the institute revised the chronology of the first six periods based on newer carbon data and calibration curves.
[src:geochronology/aspro-chronology] In Period 3 an early and late phase could be distinguished, but Periods 4 and 5 were merged.
[src:geochronology/aspro-chronology] Overall they found more overlap in time between different cultural phases between different sites.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Geochronology is different in application from biostratigraphy, which is the science of assigning sedimentary rocks to a known geological period via describing, cataloging and comparing fossil floral and faunal assemblages.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Biostratigraphy does not *directly* provide an absolute age determination of a rock, but merely places it within an *interval* of time at which that fossil assemblage is known to have coexisted.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Both disciplines work together hand in hand, however, to the point where they share the same system of naming strata (rock layers) and the time spans utilized to classify sublayers within a stratum.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] The science of geochronology is the prime tool used in the discipline of chronostratigraphy, which attempts to derive absolute age dates for all fossil assemblages and determine the geologic history of the Earth and extraterrestrial bodies.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] By measuring the amount of radioactive decay of a radioactive isotope with a known half-life, geologists can establish the absolute age of the parent material.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] A number of radioactive isotopes are used for this purpose, and depending on the rate of decay, are used for dating different geological periods.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] More slowly decaying isotopes are useful for longer periods of time, but less accurate in absolute years.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] With the exception of the radiocarbon method, most of these techniques are actually based on measuring an increase in the abundance of a radiogenic isotope, which is the decay-product of the radioactive parent isotope.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Two or more radiometric methods can be used in concert to achieve more robust results.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Most radiometric methods are suitable for geological time only, but some such as the radiocarbon method and the 40Ar/39Ar dating method can be extended into the time of early human life and into recorded history.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] A series of related techniques for determining the age at which a geomorphic surface was created (exposure dating), or at which formerly surficial materials were buried (burial dating).
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Exposure dating uses the concentration of exotic nuclides (e.g.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] 10Be, 26Al, 36Cl) produced by cosmic rays interacting with Earth materials as a proxy for the age at which a surface, such as an alluvial fan, was created.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Burial dating uses the differential radioactive decay of 2 cosmogenic elements as a proxy for the age at which a sediment was screened by burial from further cosmic rays exposure.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Luminescence dating techniques observe 'light' emitted from materials such as quartz, diamond, feldspar, and calcite.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Many types of luminescence techniques are utilized in geology, including optically stimulated luminescence (OSL), cathodoluminescence (CL), and thermoluminescence (TL).
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Thermoluminescence and optically stimulated luminescence are used in archaeology to date 'fired' objects such as pottery or cooking stones and can be used to observe sand migration.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Incremental dating techniques allow the construction of year-by-year annual chronologies, which can be fixed (*i.e.* linked to the present day and thus calendar or sidereal time) or floating.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] A sequence of paleomagnetic poles (usually called virtual geomagnetic poles), which are already well defined in age, constitutes an apparent polar wander path (APWP).
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Such a path is constructed for a large continental block.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] APWPs for different continents can be used as a reference for newly obtained poles for the rocks with unknown age.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] For paleomagnetic dating, it is suggested to use the APWP in order to date a pole obtained from rocks or sediments of unknown age by linking the paleopole to the nearest point on the APWP.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Two methods of paleomagnetic dating have been suggested: (1) the angular method and (2) the rotation method.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] The first method is used for paleomagnetic dating of rocks inside of the same continental block.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] The second method is used for the folded areas where tectonic rotations are possible.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Magnetostratigraphy determines age from the pattern of magnetic polarity zones in a series of bedded sedimentary and/or volcanic rocks by comparison to the magnetic polarity timescale.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] The polarity timescale has been previously determined by dating of seafloor magnetic anomalies, radiometrically dating volcanic rocks within magnetostratigraphic sections, and astronomically dating magnetostratigraphic sections.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Global trends in isotope compositions, particularly carbon-13 and strontium isotopes, can be used to correlate strata.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Marker horizons are stratigraphic units of the same age and of such distinctive composition and appearance that, despite their presence in different geographic sites, there is certainty about their age-equivalence.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Fossil faunal and floral assemblages, both marine and terrestrial, make for distinctive marker horizons.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Tephrochronology is a method for geochemical correlation of unknown volcanic ash (tephra) to geochemically fingerprinted, dated tephra.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Tephra is also often used as a dating tool in archaeology, since the dates of some eruptions are well-established.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] It is important not to confuse geochronologic and chronostratigraphic units.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Geochronological units are periods of time, thus it is correct to say that *Tyrannosaurus rex* lived during the Late Cretaceous Epoch.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] Chronostratigraphic units are geological material, so it is also correct to say that fossils of the genus *Tyrannosaurus* have been found in the Upper Cretaceous Series.
[src:geochronology/geochronology] In the same way, it is entirely possible to visit an Upper Cretaceous Series deposit – such as the Hell Creek deposit where the *Tyrannosaurus* fossils were found – but it is naturally impossible to visit the Late Cretaceous Epoch as that is a period of time.
